At the end of the trade, the Prague Stock Exchange turned negative
After Tuesday morning’s crash, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilize the US financial sector, is thus also noticeable here.
Shares fall in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, although the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese equities from the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"Hesitation about the U.S. bailout will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would suffer the consequences.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the proposed financial system support, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly K<0xC4><0x8D>12 billion).
The legislators thus reject the call for support of President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks went through a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indexes fell the most in 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a drop of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress caved: U.S. government can pump $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congressional leaders and President George W. Bush’s administration have agreed on a broader form of financial aid deal for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in the talks over the adoption of a bailout in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner) in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, the chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor to revive the financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market aid can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing opinions on what form the market stabilization package should take," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with the American Minister of Finance Henry Paulson, in order to give the substance of the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial firms the unsaleable real estate assets that are driving financial firms into considerable losses and threatening the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with this market recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are ensuring that Congress will reach a final agreement by Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the Congress decision could affect Monday's trade.
However, for the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two houses of Congress will proceed to the vote, or if the negotiations will not risk being blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will undergo many changes.
The total amount intended to be used by the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be made available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount, by following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
President Bush Welcomes Progress in Negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put him in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain financing for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
Spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors from losses, the settlement of rebates, and the timeline.
The new law also provides for the limitation of the said golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and it establishes a committee, which will ensure the supervision of the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and have made significant progress toward an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides help for property owners, who have trouble paying.
The government should negotiate new down payments in the case of mortgages that it will buy, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization is going to be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that we do not know what the mechanism and the price of the purchase of problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
“It’s much more important that congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that we commit to it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at the moment," Marek stressed.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are piled up vinyl records on your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, namely compressed music, to put it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would struggle to bear headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the basic functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to play music and movies, record them, has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have in your pocket a small computer.
Since no refrigerator can grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without its drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important energy goofs.
There are few mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are much more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of recharging, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least efficient.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
One can, of course, record music directly to the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
As for the players, you do not need, except for (iPod), any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves, classified by the performer's name, album title, style, or user judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, focus on the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3.
Virtually every mobile phone is capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the formats of music that the mobile or the player is able to read.
Everyone can play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have just that format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), meanwhile, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a music mobile.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to quickly made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile phone around.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which practically all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three thousand four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also provided with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone can secure the order of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
In principle, the basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive come out even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you are among the most demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile-walkman instead (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are provided with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control comes close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series phones have the same user menu as separately sold MP3 players, is the one that has gone the furthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe...
The Czech mobile market is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz many times that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no more room for another operator, spoke with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently not very lucky anymore (by the way, now it would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable fall in prices, to which conventional operators must also react.
Yet, even before trouble-makers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those heard in our country today were being heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could be a real success.
We don’t have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
In addition, behind Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they need much fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators are emerging as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as cheap as its competitors in the UK.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work in our country as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not hidden, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be promising.
From unofficial information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2’s statement: “We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis.”
“It is virtually impossible for a virtual carrier to appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time frame, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Instead, Vodafone is focusing on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most contributions from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
What good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to get along like thieves at a fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon is also proof of this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon lends itself as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: “Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands.
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, it is not only about the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
No agreement of this type has been concluded at the moment, because the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori presented enough interest for conventional operators, "said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in response to our question.
Such a statement would not come as a surprise to representatives of operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and among other things also take care that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreigner, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile phone services."
However, pushing for an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a gasoline price strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and the hard fight of the competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore none of them has a corresponding increased responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even in the telecoms regulator," Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose another view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
Now, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators visibly proceed in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility back on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common turn in communications, by means of which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the matter.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Regrettably, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act did not succeed in extending the powers of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests apparently lie elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a question of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Special mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are talking about happens, it could be a transgression of the contractual conditions that we would examine and that could lead to a stop of the collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová answered our question on this problem.
Nevertheless, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they can not fully dispose of it, in the way of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
This is precisely what should seem strange to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, there is another question at the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable drop in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, the traditional operators were trying more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies intervened in the developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up with the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies treat this issue in the manner of a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we can not get rid of the impression that the confusion in the skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw in the towel after the axe.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear here, the Czech mobile market may get moving again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensively than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On the occasion of Czech Nationality Day on Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> B<0xC4><0x9B>lohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, a choir performance and an instrumental version.
Singing is provided by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD>nková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiá<0xC5><0xA1> and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
B<0xC4><0x9B>lohlávek considers the Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers, as well as the choir, have a good diction, so that we understand the lyrics, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j was first sung in 1834 on the stage of Stavovské divadlo (Theatre of States) in Fidlova<0xC4><0x8D>ka (Kermesse des savetiers), the Czech original by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of Franti<0xC5><0xA1>ek <0xC5><0xA0>kroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
