Prague’s public transport (MHD) will introduce, on Wednesday, the chip in their ticketing system
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Pra<0xC5><0xBE>sk<0xC3><0xBD> Dopravn<0xC3><0xAD> podnik (Prague Transport Agency) as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about a hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravn<0xC3><0xAD> podnik (Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD> Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>lyl, Ro<0xC5><0x9B>l.
Starting from yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy the coupons by internet on the web pages of the Dopravn<0xC3><0xAD> podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people enjoyed the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can permanently forget about the counters in metro stations, where they had until now to stomp impatiently in long queues in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon online and it will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen M<0xC4><0x9B>stská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these points of contact, there is a ticket office with trained staff available to passengers, who will help those interested with the purchase over the internet and, in addition, will register the coupon they have purchased on their card," says project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
Next to the libraries, it will also be possible to register the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, reminiscent of composting machines tickets and passengers may have already noticed them in metro stations Roztyly, Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD> added.
An automaton will check the coupon instead of the driver
The machines that will be running from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply enter the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
Namely in peri-urban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of central Bohemia to access the capital.
"In the integrated trains in Pra<0xC5><0xBE>ská integrovaná doprava (Prague's integrated transport), the controllers are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of the coupons;" explained ticket control Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid, which designs the schedules of the Prague public transport.
Peri-urban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver’s box.
When boarding it is therefore necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard at the place indicated on the side of the cashier.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"In case the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing simpler than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take the peri-urban buses and will not remember the date on which the validity of their coupon expires, can return to the vending machines, originally used to save the coupons on the card.
This is where the information about the validity of their document will be displayed on the screen of the device.
The Sudetenland demanded a referendum in the United States.
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that <0xC5><0xA0>umava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna (South Bohemian Scientific Library).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
Among other things, this stems from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna.
Germans from <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> Krumlov ask the US president in the letter not to allow "<0xC5><0xA1>umavská <0xC5><0xBE>upa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter, signed "People, whom the fate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava is close to heart," reads.
Given that the rallying to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, disrespectful attitude, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take into his hands the protectorate of <0xC5><0xA0>umava for now and forever.
“We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into consideration the opinion of the quarter of a million of the inhabitants,” the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubts the opinion of the Germans of <0xC5><0xA0>umava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the US, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them would admit to such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would obtain for the Sudetenland a certain type of autonomy.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they got home, the Czech would be profitable for them,” Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans living in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, as a result of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that intends to launch, Wednesday, the Ministry of transport.
Minister Ale<0xC5><0xA1> <0xC5><0x98>eb<0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek's office believes it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, on the internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and drinking while driving.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
It wants above all to touch the conscience of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
