Olmert would give back in exchange for peace almost all the occupied territories
Ehud Olmert, the president of Israel’s provisional government, called for the return of virtually all of the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made the statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
“We must reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all,” Olmert told the daily.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to cede to the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), since without that, peace will not be made," he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants security in Jerusalem, and above all does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert said, referring to the two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens injured.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
“Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It won’t work,” he said later.
Retreat from the Golan Heights
Olmert also called for Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he said was an indispensable condition for a peace deal with Syria.
This would also require some efforts on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing to make peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan retreat," he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to give up their current relations with Iran; they will have to give up their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to give up the constant support they give to the terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), Al-Qaeda (terrorist network), as well as that of Jihad (holy war) in Iraq.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards in the coach illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long distance coach is forbidden
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the journey.
"If you want to strictly and formally comply with the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," transport ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka said.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old flight attendant died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the bus's path.
The girl was unfortunately sitting next to the driver, in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake abruptly, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The long-distance buses Student Agency do not have standing spaces; this was confirmed in Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
"This is an issue that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any travel of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the ride as long as they have their own seat,” he said.
The Law Ignores the Steward
“There is no one-size-fits-all legal interpretation of the role of steward – no legal prescription deals with that role.
On the other hand, there is also no legal requirement to prohibit the carrier from offering services.
The law on road transport knows only the term vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties," adds spokesman Hanzelka more ambiguously.
Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the director of the Department of Road Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
"It all depends on whether the bus has permission to offer standing seats in its approval.
It's all in there," he said.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing places and a higher permitted speed and long distance coaches without standing place with the highest permitted speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like on the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) in transport safety, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"During regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in airplanes.
There, too, it is not certain when turbulence will occur and the air hostess may bump her head.”
“If the bus braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously apply.
In the same way as in an urban bus or a tram.
The carrier has to manage the safety of the stewards through internal requirements," he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the problem is not solved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only coach carrier to offer the services of stewards.
He hired two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their trade to be a risky trade.
"Nevertheless, as soon as I get the impression that this is a risky trade, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper upon boarding.
It would also cut costs,” he said.
The concern for safety is the reason given by the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvin, who ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have any hostesses. We have opposed it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident," he told T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz a year ago.
A huge tragedy has happened
A young hostess from the Plze<0xC5><0x88> region, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a turn signal and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter trying to avoid him by means of a sudden maneuver, but he brushed him by his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura refused to allow the two seats reserved for the stewards to be sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to book these places, they are blocked."
The company plans to file a complaint against the driver of the truck.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but with regard to financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been under development for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could clarify the movements of stewards on board the coach.
"However, it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
To tell the truth, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the system of points, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says the expert Ho<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>n.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of the stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers," Hanzelka concluded, adding that the control of the safety of buses is under the power of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
