Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, insisted the Federal Minister of Finance only a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word ‘relatively’ and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared from crisis movements.
This one actually happened this weekend.
The financier of the Bavarian real estate Hypo Real Estate (HRE), alongside the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a loan of one billion to protect itself from the turbulence of the markets.
A person with confidence in the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are issued up to an amount of 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from private banks as much as from public banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's cash reserve had been reduced from 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, the rate of equity also had slightly weakened from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Outstanding and net profits from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period last year, while profits from the allocation of receivables and specified securities and the termination of provisions in credit operations had fallen by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it is only thanks to the significant profits from the reimbursement of the downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the companies of Konzern, that the earnings deficit of about 16 percent turned out to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had at first speculated badly on industrial real estate loans, which then had been subsidiaryized to the bank Aareal.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more actively involved in infrastructure projects and in financing joint projects between private investors and the state (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect that still remains rather unclear.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had been cut to two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate is, since the acquisition of Depfa, a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other refinancing-dependent institutions on the interbank market as it has no client deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has once again dried up considerably, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a part - about 50 billion euros - of all the credits of the Depfa of a short-term means of refinancing.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of order currently.
Other sources say that the refinancing would be provided through the funds until the end of 2009.
Georg Funke, Chairman of the Board of Management of HRE, however, explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for the Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group's market capacity is now assured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors can only hope so.
However, given the dynamics and weightlessness of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not inconceivable that funding should not be used to its full extent.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest releases, still on the verge of insolvency Sunday evening, this rescue at least temporary will not succeed in reassuring minds either.
The share price fell 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of second-tier loans are falling.
The most affected are especially the investment funds of the former daughter company W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg Hypo and those of course that have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of the bank Hypo Real Estate previously appeared to be an alternative speculative investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the same institute that brought the crisis into the institution by the purchase of the bank Depfa.
As long as the issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still prepared to support the system, a reduction in arrears over time can be assumed.
Or it will happen what no one dares hope at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of renewed rumors of partial nationalization, the probability that approached safety has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve sleepless nights above all for long-term creditors on the decision whether to part with their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line to defer losses for the next few years on the next capital gains tax automatically levied.
