Rats have feelings too.
A rat or a cockroach flees in the face of danger, does that mean that it also feels fear?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having until now been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, one can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or in general of consciousness, we enter into terrains that are difficult to practice because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees, or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the awareness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of Man: since a large part of his existence is related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, cannot be measured or analyzed on the basis of our own experience because of this particular hardware, then its observation poses big problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies of the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does this mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its sequels, such as the reactions of the body) takes over the RAM.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our fickle nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the corporeal sensation regions of the cortex and brainstem, just as Jaak Pankseep does, however, focus more on the brainstem.
As this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could quite participate in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it to be indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in both men and rats is likely to be felt as fear in both cases: yet how could one check whether rats and men feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in the face of danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Admittedly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brains, cockroaches, on the other hand, do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem causing the sensations?
And even if we could prove this for humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are likely to be completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I’d rather explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is necessary on the nervous level to the extent that the same thing is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I don't explore language and consciousness in rats, or sensations, I don't know if they exist.
This could be judged as short-term, but I’d rather move forward than constantly bumping into a wall.
I am an emotional pragmatist.
