Hidden in the development of its huge park, a few miles from sunny, bright and giant Orlando, lies a quiet little town where pride and the complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, first all-black town to be incorporated, childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, this description she made in 1935, is no longer so simple to make nowadays." The town with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of guavas, two schools and no prison."
It has now become a city of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora Festival in Eatonville to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in a variety of ways, the city she describes—which became touristic thanks to its inclusion in The Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project’s Florida tourist guide—remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston said that the rural black population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knowing us so little, doesn't know what he's losing."
Even if this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who invoked an open dialogue on the theme of race, many here remain cautious of the foreign gaze.
“We’re very careful about how we tell the story,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a longtime resident and the city’s oldest parishioner.
“It has to be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It represents both a historical model of a black takeover and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of Southern black rural culture - sometimes scorned, sometimes acclaimed - which recalls the birth of American slavery.
This would explain why the residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through sincere, dialect-filled books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed this city, located just off Route 17, a road that crosses central Florida, often forgotten, which ends in a chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold as a cash register in life as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, which was later divided into several private parts.
“After the road on the left,” she writes, “you’ll find the modern brown and white public school, with its well-preserved gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller has always taken care of, although he barely knows how to read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds as well as everything that can be used by passers-by.
So, in barely a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn’t really a portrait that everyone liked.
Zora described the reality well," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's young daughters Hurston immortalized, citing the colorless songs, performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who returned frequently after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town unannounced in a big Chevrolet with a cigarette in his mouth and wore pants here, where even today, we are proud of traditional clothes.
