“People were always happy to see Zora,” he said.
But he adds further, swinging in his chair from the backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was certainly baptized, that "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in some sort of grave, at Fort Pierce, Fla, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no major commemoration, no plaque for the general public.
I don’t think they understood the contribution or legacy she gave to the world,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A crucial moment occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to move a five-lane highway into the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community’s main two-lane street.
The development of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made just as Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing dispute brought hatred to the gates of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of young white people would come and throw oranges or objects at people sitting on the side," Franklin said.
“A lady has even died.”
They threw a watermelon out of their car.”
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s request for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown v. Board of Education “insulting rather than glorifying my race.”
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some respects, has diluted the cohesion of Eatonville and weakened the confidence of young people.
