This lasted, she added, until the teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
“You don’t kiss your white teacher because he’s white – I mean there’s a cultural dividing line here,” Ms Nathiri said.
Civil rights, moreover, have created space for many other Zora Neale Hurston—black writers, actors, and artists who have gone beyond prejudice, such as herself, armed with joyful self-confidence and lines of conduct such as: “How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!”
This is beyond me.”
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited Hurston's unmarked grave and began struggling to revive his reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a real best seller, reintroduced it to the American canons.
The highway project came just as the most famous girl in Eatonville had regained her appeal.
And this time, Hurston’s old neighbors consider her a savior.
The community began organizing a Hurston Festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of this highway.
Hundreds of fans came to the festival's opening two years later, and many return in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the county pushed back the highway proposal.
"The fiasco of the five-lane highway, extremely fast, a real civic pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Miss Boyd summed it up by stating that "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has attended our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents began to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been listed as a Historic City since 1998.
A single-theme library (renamed Hurston of course) opened in 2006, on a magnificent re-paved Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back street on a rainy summer day, small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(There are now 90 percent black people.)
Strangers who come to discover Eatonville's history, its raison d'<0xC3><0xAA>tre, are still treated with caution.
