Many in Eatonville, like Miss Jones, a courageous teacher with a soft spot for bright red, are still afraid that their island community will be well understood.
However, with the expansion of the Hurston festival, a certain level of local pride emerged.
Young people in particular, tend to view Eatonville as Hurston viewed his entire race: beautiful, problematic and all, neither better nor worse, but as proud, creative, hard-working, crazy and mixed as the other ethnic and racial groups in America.
The voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, is one of sincere civic affection and plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or police forces, who need additional forces.
