Included in the program of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, bigger every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera moments of personality of the flamenco stars ".
With the "People's Song of the Mines" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, recall classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and that surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the song itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essential and the magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a moment or two.
I believe that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you do not know or who give you only a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata Gallery, located at number 20, rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16th.
