Recidivists of alcohol at the wheel will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for alcohol, to install in his vehicle a system that prevents starting the vehicle drunk, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered as a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is the reintegration of the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the General Directorate of Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists stopped for driving drunk more than once, take the car.
The alcoholock would avoid this since it is a system plugged into the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than authorized.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of infringements in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This is due to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, nevertheless, the reform made by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install in school buses this system as has been done in France.
