Talking while sleeping
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
This is a mild sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one who talks at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with cries, tears, long speeches ...
In the event that somniloquy becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep alteration that can be cured (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as sleepiness appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless since he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is unusual), don’t be tempted to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because while sleeping, he is not conscious in order to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, do not worry, this is nothing very bad, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
