Sarkozy to meet angry fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour through Brittany.
Faced with the demonstration of strength of the fishermen who have strongly disturbed Monday the accesses of several Breton and Norman ports, the president of the Republic has decided to go Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec, in the Finist<0xC3><0xA8>re, to meet their representatives.
They promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he will "come up with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit that falls at the same time as a general assembly of the "crisis committee" created by the Breton fishermen to obtain measures against the soaring prices of diesel, which reached a record at more than 1.14 euros per liter on average.
According to the spokesman of the Elysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and remuneration of sailors".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected by the fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they carried out snail operations in Morbihan and Calvados, causing closures of nearly 10 km.
The marina of Quiberon was also blocked, but the links to Belle-<0xC3><0xAE>le did not stop.
A filter dam has been put in place on the Quiberon peninsula.
The sailors have already shown their determination Monday by burning, at dawn, tires and pallets in front of the fuel depots of the ports of Brest, and Lorient, while demonstrations were taking place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as Les Sables d'Olonne, in the Vendée, where trawlers remained on the quay, or Le Havre, where some twenty boats blocked the movements of commercial vessels.
The fishermen of La Turballe and Croisic, in Loire-Atlantique, stopped in the evening the blockade of the important Total refinery of Donges.
Those in Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait for Wednesday's meeting at the ministry to decide on possible actions.
At Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" must decide on Tuesday on the follow-up to the movement and its participation in the interview scheduled at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials of the National Fisheries Committee, which has not supported their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not let anything go" and "do not wish to move to Paris", announced for example Liliane Cariou, the president of the committee of fisheries of Lorient.
The professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per liter but they estimate that the break-even point of a boat is only reached with diesel less than 0.30 euro per liter.
