Some confess not to have even voted: "What good, since they will do what they want with my voice," says a young man.
They do not believe that the regime that has made a good impression on foreign observers with the aim of regaining its language with the European Union is ready to make a democratic turn.
Sanctions, including a visa ban for 40 Belarusian leaders and the freezing of some assets, could be lifted if the elections were deemed clean by observers.
They were not, according to the opposition.
"We have been kept away from the electoral commissions and our observers have not been able to participate in the recount," said Yury Potemkin, spokesman for the Union of Democratic Forces, a heterogeneous grouping of twelve parties.
"This is a cosmetic change," said Alexander Milinkievich, a former candidate of the opposition in the 2006 presidential election and leader of the pro-European movement, "because the important thing is who counts the votes, and in our country, it is the executive power.
If opposition members enter parliament, they will have been appointed, not elected.
But their entry into parliament can mean space on television, meetings in the regions and proposed laws.
The opposition must therefore enter into the political game because "dialogue with the European Union must begin.
For if our economy, which is heavily indebted to Russia, goes into crisis, and we do not reform, we risk becoming a protectorate of Russia.
We want to be independent.”
The opposition feared that the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which had followed the electoral process, would recognize the validity of the vote.
She points out that the turnout figures seem too high, and that the generalization of advance voting (26% of voters in Minsk) has opened the voice to all manipulations.
"You noticed that there was an election, you?" asks the Social Democratic leader Alexandre Kozulin, one of the last two political prisoners released in August this year.
