As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party was over, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon, in Quebec City, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is trying to get elected on the occasion of today's by-election.
"To push back the limits of our last great northern frontier": this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining in the main lines, at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, was projected a kind of image mill.
Spectacular shots of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec seen by "Google Maps", maps, etc. were looped on three huge screens.
Great means as in the election period.
At the press conference, the Prime Minister refused to rule out the possibility that he would call an election this fall, even though he noted that his schedule was very busy.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth part of a "vision" that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic space", which includes a labour agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the Prime Minister's speeches recently, the opening of the North - the northern territory at the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, limited himself to explaining why the North was "a jewel of immense potential", but did not give a deadline, investment amounts, or specific priority in future projects.
At most a few avenues of what could be further developed: notably hydroelectricity, the forest, but especially the mining sector, boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamond," according to Charest's listing.
This "territory twice as big as France", "it's home, it's in Quebec.
Not only is it at home, but it is in us,” he insisted, as if to show that he was soliciting a national founding myth.
Quebec has built a lot in its relationship with the North, he said: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
“It’s up to us, it’s our future,” he added, after taking a theatrical break to contemplate the immense map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the Prime Minister said at the press briefing.
“This is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has not been an agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I reiterate that position on behalf of the government," he said.
“With climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North,” he said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which will open year-round due to melting ice.
