The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice-President of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, it claims that the world’s largest gold company filed a six-million-dollar defamation suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house in order to launch a “transparent public debate.”
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of public opinion that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally held by the exchange of ideas and not by truncheons.
It was therefore enough for the mine to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold appears to distrust public opinion and dismisses petitions and letters of support for Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can at the same time call for a "public" debate while despising the views of that same public?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers only to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag suit (pursuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice against the authors of Black Canada ordering them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s prosecution is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth that are essential to any democratic society.
It denies, en bloc, the right to citation from credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss matters that the rich companies of this world do not like in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has a long history of managing debates and disagreements and resolving conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate prosecution makes it clear that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the academic world, as it is to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the leaders of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective in the marketplace," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done to shield the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the bottom line: If we don’t do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” Gregg said.
Negotiations had turned to the sprint in recent hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would cause on the mood of investors.
The deadline we had agreed upon was the opening of the markets this morning.
Belatedly associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election have been rather supportive of the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction that we are forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that to allow owners to keep their homes and that on the salary of leaders of companies rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no reason to be happy.
But these measures are necessary," he said on US television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: “I’d like to see the details, but I hope so.”
“The broad outlines I’ve read [show] that this is something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsaleable claims of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulting in a liquidity freeze and the disbandment of banks and institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who overturned the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to have emerged from this impasse since Democrats accepted that some of the troubled companies’ “toxic” assets were only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round out the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which another 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another vote in Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will earn it dividends in case of profit and that it can resell when the turmoil has passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay foreclosure procedures for housing attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance pay paid to executives of affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given the go-ahead.
Indeed, voices continued to be raised yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that benefits taxpayers.”
The leader of a small group in Congress known as the “Skeptics’ Caucus,” Rep. Brad Sherman (D-Calif.) presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred prominent economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas said it was giving up on acquiring its competitor in the midst of shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s 20 largest banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
In exchange, we get a voting right in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that the times are looking uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all the loans outstanding at the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
