The psychology of auctioneering: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw a neurological picture of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lotto, while the other group took part in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over-bid of a third, the whole located under the brain stem, called striatum, moved intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the “self-stimulation” mechanism of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight in the face of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers pursued financial surveillance analyses.
In these, three groups outbid a partner in a variety of circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they thus placed them.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out the winner of the game, then they would receive an additional 15 dollars, as a reward.
While the third group received that $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis in one was on victory, while in the other, on failure.
By thus proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to higher stakes than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories, leading now to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred thousand people are infected with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand people receive treatment, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected with the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, upset stomach and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know that they have the virus because the pathogenic gene sneakily destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
The contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic cirrhosis of the liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
