Intelligent car mimics drone flight
What better way to develop obstacle-avoiding technologies than by imitating an obstacle detector that already exists in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the stunning project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting idea, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C-type self-robotized control system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval-shaped, which in reality, looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and technological public relations department of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles in a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates distances and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver right away.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot car, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If this were not the case, the mini-auto robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, acceleration and slowdown as maneuvers available to the mini robot car.
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, which makes their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism must process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory with a capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance, which Nissan estimates will make its way into mass-produced cars within the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in his way.
