Mp3 players pointed fingers, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is announced by the European Commission, which, in a statement issued in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
According to the report, “5 to 10 percent of those who listen to music at full volume for at least five years using portable music devices for more than an hour a day per week are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume, can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” Kuneva said.
“According to scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise generated by them.
The scientists confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit this data using solutions such as reducing the levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods, risk permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
