The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the rescue plan of $ 700 billion approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is yesterday's New York Times that confirms it by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the states of the Center and South.
The soul, precisely, that has been felt in a despotic way with the vote that I spoke to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake foreshadows or already leaves to run: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and may be not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been brewing for some time, to the point that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the reactualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign-state, with respect to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that obviously have close relations with foreign countries, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the question, or it does not have much to say: the obvious proof is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and the various national strategies, fails to decide on any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection of credits: when one goes through a difficult period, only the states possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the more recent economic developments tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at a stroke of one hand, that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather unmaterial things such as the Internet.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, provides for a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow zone.
And in addition, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of countries of the West.
