The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
That is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to hold a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal a perfect grip.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, showed that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "detaches easily from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
MARKING WALLS? – “This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but the researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
At the moment, there are no superheroes.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also committed to the search for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, the Californian researchers presented an adhesive formed of microfibers like hair, which cleans itself from dust during movement on a surface to ensure a perfect and constant adhesion.
Medications: never with fruit juices.
Pay attention to the juice of grapefruit, orange and apple.
These drinks, consumed especially in the summer because they are refreshing and rich in vitamins, when combined with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices whether they are, in box or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia, he launches a new alarm to reduce certain health effects: it is enough a glass of grapefruit juice, oranges and ricotta.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for being held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stem and neurological drugs, up to toxic levels.
It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a newsletter dated two years, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger derived from this mix and to pay attention to what one drinks, if one takes drugs such as, for example, Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY PAMPLEMOUSE- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the department of pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: “These findings are generally immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies who will have to change the information notes of the drugs if necessary.
It is always advisable to read the illustrative papers of the medicines that one takes, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to address clearly to the doctor or pharmacist "said the expert to the agency Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics goes to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a well-known New York Times columnist.
Krugman is one of the greatest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy solutions.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of the Enron bankruptcy, Krugman had written in an article published in the New York Times that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on the history of the United States.
A forecast that sparked many controversies, and which was blamed on the economist for years, but which has now turned out to be accurate.
“I am surprised and even a little shocked at how quickly the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from public attention,” Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the European Central Bank's executive committee, Krugman is a "high-value economist", but also a very aggressive "disseminator", particularly critical of the excesses of liberalism of the Bush administration.
Open Office, this is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to reach more and more users, from the home to the office, from professionals to the public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work, carried out by volunteer developers, monitored by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is shown to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen, and the revised and less austere interface, to other more important ones, such as the compatibility born for the latest Apple Mac OS X operating system, and support for the new ISODF format (Open Document Format).
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some functions specific to certain modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by email, or to import PDF files into the graphic development module, maintaining the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front, it is possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents that unite the typical graphic of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a text editor.
The collaboration between several people is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts on the changes, in the elaboration of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a color of comments for better recognition during the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some OpenOffice features to the web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they should issue the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and is in addition to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual available in addition, for the Linux operating system.
Upon request, the installation CD can be shipped to your home or workplace.
And if the theme of free can be a way to disseminate it in homes, it is precisely in business, that Open Office next tries the big challenge, already being able to count on various projects carried out in public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer a training, consultation and assistance service, ideal for small and medium-sized companies, which could also open up to business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the equivalent video writing of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for rival presentations of PowerPoint; Dbase, such as the famous Access, is the program that allows to work on databases; finally Drwa is the graphic module.
Target for 2008, reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today there are almost 3 million and 600 miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the expected figure
