Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student housing market is not in crisis
According to the latest survey of the Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families from abroad must support - explains the head of the Sunia design office, Laura Mariani - in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of generalized increase has begun even for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free, unregistered, rent-free, sub-rental contracts.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax, are necessary to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it goes from 650 euros minimum (Black Belt area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (€550 for a single) for the areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
One can only save if one moves away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for bed, it takes 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities eliminate the historic cinemas.
Historical movie theaters close in favor of Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-screen cinemas, and the death of mono-screen consumption in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems to us inescapable and incontestable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a part of the way and so many emotions", observes the director of the Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Jury of Cannes, and which always told the story of a
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have mostly paid the cost: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Roma Emilia leads with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-screen cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of the credit in favor of the merchants: the antecedent debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would need between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Notably, Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried by these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-screen cinemas in the historic centers and in the outskirts.
Among the planned regulations, there are measures of tax facilities in favor of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the zone with limited traffic, and will have special rates for parking and in some car parks.
"It is an initiative that I like," Giuseppe Tornatore observes, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by implementing other measures.
It is obvious, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradiso cinema" which I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, I turn the other way so as not to see the panels blackened by the dust.
