When energy is born from waves, now the big ones are launching.
This is an disproportionate deposit that occupies more than 70% of the surface of the planet and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which giants like Chevron have set their eyes, and now are trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boom to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity need could be met by sea swell operating systems.
This amount would be double that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be the currents and the tides..
Colossus to attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years after that, more and more candidates among these companies dedicated to traditional energy have always focused on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies," a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which travel the path of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, due to the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create a big problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which, in turn, powers a generator.
The energy is sent to shore through underwater cables.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, awaiting a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines from New York’s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, right now deserves the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, with others, look to the coasts, have invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and plans investments up to 35 million in 2009.
